      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "From an environmental standpoint, congestion pricing is overwhelmingly supported as a necessary policy for meeting climate targets. By directly disincentivizing driving in dense areas, it forces a modal shift toward cleaner public transit and active transportation. The logic is sound: fewer idling cars mean immediate reductions in harmful urban emissions. Any resistance to this is usually rooted in political resistance to change, not in environmental science.",
      "source": "target",
